aa(lp127
VSo I decided to build a prototype.
p128
aVI went to a video terminal connected to Harvard's time-sharing system
p129
aVand got to work.
p130
aVOne of the first problems that I ran into was:
p131
aVHow do you represent values in formulas?
p132
aVLet me show you what I mean.
p133
aVI thought that you would point somewhere,
p134
aVtype in some words, then type in some somewhere else,
p135
aVput in some numbers and some more numbers, point where you want the answer.
p136
aVAnd then point to the first, press minus, point to the second,
p137
aVand get the result.
p138
aVThe problem was: What should I put in the formula?
p139
aVIt had to be something the computer knew what to put in.
p140
aVAnd if you looked at the formula,
p141
aVyou needed to know where on the screen it referred to.
p142
aVThe first thing I thought was the programmer way of doing it.
p143
aVThe first time you pointed to somewhere,
p144
aVthe computer would ask you to type in a unique name.
p145
aVIt became pretty clear pretty fast that that was going to be too tedious.
p146
aVThe computer had to automatically make up the name and put it inside.
p147
aVSo I thought, why not make it be the order in which you create them?
p148
aVI tried that. Value 1, value 2.
p149
aVPretty quickly I saw that if you had more than a few values
p150
aVyou'd never remember on the screen where things were.
p151
aa(lp152
VThen I said, why not instead of allowing you to put values anywhere,
p153
aVI'll restrict you to a grid?
p154
aVThen when you pointed to a cell,
p155
aVthe computer could put the row and column in as a name.
p156
aVAnd, if I did it like a map and put ABC across the top and numbers along the side,
p157
aVif you saw B7 in a formula,
p158
aVyou'd know exactly where it was on the screen.
p159
aVAnd if you had to type the formula in yourself, you'd know what to do.
p160
aVRestricting you to a grid helped solve my problem.
p161
aVIt also opened up new capabilities, like the ability to have ranges of cells.
p162
aVBut it wasn't too restrictive \u2014
p163
aVyou could still put any value, any formula, in any cell.
p164
aVAnd that's the way we do it to this day, almost 40 years later.
